<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>When I hit PoP and started testing various mobs, it seemed that even yard trash lost more like 5% health or even less per pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->In other words, the damage per pet had decreased.  If a yard trash mob has 15k hitpoints, then 5% is 750 damage.  750 damage for how much mana?  400.  That's a 1.875 effeciency.  I realize focus items and such factor in but consider Firebolt of Tallon's unspec/unfocused effeciency: 3.84.  That's a 104% improvement!<br>
<br>
hypothetical example:<br>
<br>
power = dps*hp<br>
Healing mage dps = 140(nukes) + 65(pet) + 10(DS) = 215<br>
Healing mage hps = 3500(pet hp) + 2300 healing<br>
<br>
I estimate that would take around 3600 unspecialized mana. That could chain 9 unspecialized pets.<br>
<br>
Chaining mage dps = 30(pet)<br>
Chaining mage hps = 3000(pet hp) + 27,000 (9 chained pets)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>MageHealer Power</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: 215*5300 = 1,139,500<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hypotetical mob</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: 75*15000 = 1,125,000<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Chaining Mage Power</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: 30*30000 = 1,050,000<br>
<br>
Healing wins, chaining loses.  Of course the chain-petter can just keep chaining pets, but then he's spending more mana on a longer kill which won't necessarily get faster xp.  Realistically specialization and other factors will enter in, but this is just to point out the danger of assuming a positive trade time for mana.<br>
<br>
And the mobs I kill are nothing special really, just yard trash in tier one zones, PoD in particular-- but not the baby fly things.  Yes some mobs are light blue but they give significantly more experience per kill than dark blue luclin mobs did.  I also figure that killing these will give me practice for tackling mobs in PoV and PoS.<br>
