<br>
Yes aggro will be an issue, aggro is always an issue with chaining. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=znailvh>Znail vh</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 354<br> <font color=#333333>(2/9/03 10:35:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=456.topic&index=157>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Brainstorm: How to fix PoP Mage soloability</span><hr size=1> Hmm, to bump into the discussion about chaining and sustaining. In a group with suficient healing and slow to keep a pet going so should sustaining be better in general as that will keep a buffed and equiped pet going. Even if chaining is cheaper in mana then healing the pet so will the pet do less damage. The only way to make up for that damage is if the extra mana is used for nukes and that isnt very convinient while chaining pets due to aggro. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2639<br> <font color=#333333>(2/9/03 12:23:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=456.topic&index=158>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Brainstorm: How to fix PoP Mage soloability</span><hr size=1> Yes I agree if you have enough support to sustain a pet indefinitely it is likely that the benefits of sustaining outweigh the benefits of chaining.  The whole reason my hypothetical scenario above worked out the way it did is because I assumed 30dps pet for the chainer and 65 for the sustainer.<br>
<br>
However, the only point in mentioning slow at all was to show that sustaining and chaining can exist side-by-side even if one solo technique is generally favored over the other.  <br>
<br>
It does not need to be slow, necessarily.  Maybe you are grouped with a wizard who alternates in stuns to decrease mob damage output.  Maybe you are duoing, two mages with air pets.  Maybe the mbos have a strong magic attack that your pets are resistant to.  Maybe the mobs are lower dps higher hps mobs.<br>
<br>
