Immlazen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2878<br> <font color=#333333>(2/11/03 4:50:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=456.topic&index=160>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Brainstorm: How to fix PoP Mage soloability</span><hr size=1> Sorry I have neglected this thread, but it deserves a lengthy reply, and I want to do some analysis first.  However:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Goladus:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You may be right about chaining not always forming an upper limit on soloability.  Some initial back-of-the-envelope estimates support the idea that against mobs with of a sufficient DPS, chaining breaks down.  However, in my pre-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> experience, I was always able to solo stronger mobs with less mana by chaining.  Also, without analysis, it seems hard to believe that healing a pet could be nearly as efficient as chaining <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(it ought not to be)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, so how could alternating nukes and heals work?  But the analysis awaits.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Immlazen:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You seem to consistantly read some position in my posts that is more extreme than I intend.  First of all, I see chaining as only one strong mage tactic, albeit an important and powerful one.  My past experience with it suggested to me that it was a good estimate of the upper bound of mage-mob solo power, but as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Goladus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> points out, I am probably mistaken with high DPS mobs.  As you also point out.<br>
<br>
Also, analyzing chaining is illuminating, because it is simpler to analyze.  The pet is probably un-buffed, or at least under-buffed, and unequipped.  It is a good estimate of raw pet power.  Sustaining pets is harder to analyze.  First, a greater variety of pets can be sustained, and in my experience, only earth is a reliable pet for chaining, especially as PTK <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Pets To Kill)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rises.  Second, because the choices the mage makes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(nuke, heal, or wait)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> dramaticly effect the outcome.<br>
<br>
I do not think it is reasonable to demand that mages solo as well as kiters post-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, although many mages clearly want to.<br>
<br>
Besides chaining or tanking, I am having good success with a technique I call <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Yoyo Rooting</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  I use an earth pet only to root, not to tank, and alternating nuke and re-root.  Thus the pet mostly avoids the mob's high DPS output.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Improved Reclaim Energy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> helps enormously: pets do get wounded during these kind of fights, and I get to reclaim most of them.  To pull it off, I need distance from the mob, so a long, narrow safe spot, running back and forth between the two safe ends.<br>
<br>
The fights are long and dangerous, but I am beginning to get the hang of them, and death is paying me fewer visits.<br>
<br>
Lastly, if a mob chews through pets in under 15 seconds, then neither chaining or sustaining is going to cut it.<br>
<br>
If non-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> experience is un-nerfed, and the consequences of doing so are not unreasonable, then I would think mages can solo steadily to 65 outside <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
If mage pets are made effectively tough enough, by whatever means <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(greater hitpoints, better pet heals, slow or stun shield)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then this will probably make mages significantly more powerful, and I am not sure that can justified.<br>
<br>
Or, perhaps as is being suggested, what mages need to do is summon themselves some <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cajones</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, put on their thinking caps, and master new tactics in order to solo from 61 to 65.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
